# Small scoped changes

Implementation changes should remain small, incremental, and easy to review. Large-scale rewrites, oversized pull requests, and broad multi-system modifications should be avoided unless explicitly planned and approved.

Apply this rule when:

- implementing features
- creating pull requests
- reviewing implementation size
- coordinating parallel work
- validating production readiness

## Agent behavior

- Ship vertical slices or narrow layers per PR; if scope grows, split into stacked PRs with clear merge order instead of one huge diff.
- For risky areas: feature flags, narrow interfaces, or scaffolding PRs first—then behavior—then cleanup—each reviewable on its own.
- When coordinating parallel work: assign disjoint slices so “small” stays true in practice, not only in intent.

## Example

```text
❌ BAD — One PR rewires auth, payments, and reporting “because they’re related” with 5k-line diff

✅ GOOD — PR1 contract + flags, PR2 service A, PR3 service B, each < reasonable review budget with tests and rollback notes
```
